<DOC><DOCNO> AP901207-0253 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NY-12-07-90 1826EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f AM-Bonds     12-07 0475</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Bonds,0600</SECOND><HEAD>Hit Six-Month Highs on Grim Economic News, Lower Interest Rates</HEAD><BYLINE>By DAVID E. KALISH</BYLINE><BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Bond prices recorded the biggest one-day jump inmore than six months on Friday, propelled by grim employmentfigures and clear signs that the Federal Reserve moved to easeinterest rates.   The Treasury's bellwether 30-year bond leaped 1} point, or$17.50 per $1,000 in face amount. Its yield, which falls whenprices rise, plunged to 8.18 percent from 8.33 percent lateThursday.   The sharp price rise in the long-term bond was the largest sinceJune 1, when 30-year prices soared 1 27-32 points on a monthlygovernment report showing a big increase in unemployment. Backthen, yields on the 30-year bond dropped to 8.44 percent from theprevious day's close of 8.57 percent.   This time around economists were expecting bad tidings inFriday's monthly report, but the news was worse than expected.   The nation's unemployment rate shot up to a three-year high of5.9 percent in November, creating the worst two-month loss sincethe depths of the 1981-82 recession, the Labor Department said.   Over five months, the number of jobless has swelled by900,000.Nearly all of the nation's industries lost jobs last month aspayrolls fell by 267,000.   ``Everybody was shocked. People got a touch spooked and said,`the Fed is going to ease on this,''' said Mike Casey,international economist at Maria Ramirez Capital Consultants in NewYork.   The market jumped on speculation that the Fed would easeinterest rates to stimulate the economy, a move that generallygives a lift to bond prices.   Suspicions seemed confirmed around midday as word among tradersspread that the central bank allowed the federal funds rate, therate banks charge each other on overnight loans, to drift down by aquarter of a percentage point to 7\ percent.   In addition, the central bank announced it would inject moneyinto the banking system to encourage banks to make more fundsavailable.   By the day's close the federal funds rate traded at 7 1-16percent, down from 7 7-16 percent late Thursday.   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, short-termmaturities rose 5-16 point to 17-32 point, intermediate maturitiesjumped 11-16 point to 1 point and long-term issues soared 1{ pointto 113-16 point, the Telerate Inc. financial information servicereported.   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in theprice of a bond with a $1,000 face value.   The Lehman Brothers Daily Treasury Bond Index, which measuresprice movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with maturitiesof a year or longer, was up 8.56 to 1,186.95.   Yields on three-month Treasury bills fell to 7.10 percent as thediscount was down 11 basis points to 6.89 percent. Yields onsix-month bills were down to 7.08 percent as the discount fell 12basis points to 6.76 percent. Yields on one-year bills fell to 7.11percent as the discount was down 12 basis points to 6.68 percent.   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yieldis the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. Thediscount is the percentage that bills are selling below the facevalue, which is paid at maturity.   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 activelytraded municipal bonds rose 1-16 point to 91 23-32. The averageyield to maturity fell to 7.47 percent from 7.48 percent lateThursday.</TEXT></DOC>